    <body>
      <head>Domingo de la Cruz</head>
      <div>

        <p>Dean of the House of Fine Arts (Casa de las Bellas Artas) in <ref cRef="entity-008467"
            >Santiago</ref>, <ref cRef="entity-005845">Chile</ref>, who also taught “analysis,
          theory, and history” at the <ref cRef="entity-008489">Santiago Conservatory of
          Music</ref>.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <p><ref cRef="entity-000771">Jeanette Schenker</ref> met Domingo de la Cruz briefly on July
          30, 1936 and delivered to him a <ref cRef="entity-002408">Universal Edition</ref>
          prospectus – most likely of her <ref cRef="entity-000632">husband</ref>'s <ref
            cRef="entity-001728"><title level="m">Der freie Satz</title></ref> – saying “I am
          bringing you, something – <hi rend="italic">a new theory</hi>!!” She arranged to send a
          package of Schenker’s work to him via the <ref cRef="entity-008481">Friedemann Music
            Shop</ref> in <ref cRef="entity-008467">Santiago</ref>. On leaving the Dean, she
          records: “I repeat a few times that the dissemination of the theory is all that matters to
          me” (travel diary, July 30, 1936). This was an important step in her campaign to bring her
          husband’s work to <ref cRef="entity-005845">Chile</ref>.</p>
      </div>

    </body>

